Simple Regression

First, load the packages we are going to use.

library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
library(e1071)

Creating the Dataset 

x = 1:20
y = x + sin(x/8)*20 + rnorm(n = 20, mean = 0 , sd = 3)
theData = data.frame(x = x, y = y)

Run Simple Regression 

dataLm = lm(formula = y ~ x, data = theData)

summary(dataLm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y ~ x, data = theData)

How well does the model perform? 

predictY = predict(dataLm, theData)
predictDf = data.frame(x = theData$x, y = predictY)
theDataY = rbind(theData, predictDf)
theDataY$type = as.factor(c(rep("Original", 20),
                  rep("Prediction", 20)))


ggplot(theDataY, aes(x = x, y = y, colour = type)) + 
     geom_point(size = 2) +
     xlim(0, 20) +
     ylim(-5, 45) +
     theme_economist() + # From ggthemes
     ggtitle("Simple Linear Regression")

RMSE of Regression Model

\[ RMSE=\sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(\hat{Y}_i-Y_i)^2} \]

rmse = function(error) {
     sqrt(mean(error^2))
}
error = dataLm$residuals
predictionRMSE = rmse(error)
predictionRMSE
## [1] 5.349325

Let’s try to improve it!

Support Vector Machines 

model = svm(y ~ x, theData)
predictY = predict(model, theData)

predictDf = data.frame(x = theData$x, y = predictY)
theDataY = rbind(theData, predictDf)
theDataY$type = as.factor(c(rep("Original", 20),
                  rep("Prediction", 20)))

Plot of Untuned SVM 

ggplot(theDataY, aes(x = x, y = y, colour = type)) + 
     geom_point(size = 2) +
     xlim(0, 20) +
     ylim(-5, 45) +
     theme_economist() + # From ggthemes
     ggtitle("SVM Prediction")

Error of Untuned SVM 

error = theData$y - predictY
rmse(error)
## [1] 2.994649

Tuning the Model 

tuneResult = tune(svm, y ~ x, data = theData,
                  ranges = list(epsilon = seq(0, 1, 0.1),
                                cost = 2^(2:9)))

print(tuneResult)
## 
## Parameter tuning of 'svm':
## 
## - sampling method: 10-fold cross validation 
## 
## - best parameters:
##  epsilon cost
##      0.1    4
## 
## - best performance: 12.22845
plot(tuneResult)

Result of Tuning 

tuneResult <- tune(svm, y ~ x,  data = theData,
                   ranges = list(epsilon = seq(0,0.2,0.01), cost = 2^(2:9))
) 
 
print(tuneResult)
## 
## Parameter tuning of 'svm':
## 
## - sampling method: 10-fold cross validation 
## 
## - best parameters:
##  epsilon cost
##     0.14    4
## 
## - best performance: 11.80493
plot(tuneResult)

Here it appears that the models with a cost between 0-30 and an epsilon of .11 behave best. The summary shows us this and it’s the darkest part of the region.

Error of Tuned SVM 

tunedModel <- tuneResult$best.model
tunedModelY <- predict(tunedModel, theData) 
 
error <- theData$y - tunedModelY  
 
# this value can be different on your computer
# because the tune method  randomly shuffles the data
tunedModelRMSE <- rmse(error)  
tunedModelRMSE
## [1] 2.869616
tunedDf = data.frame(x = theData$x, y = tunedModelY)
theDataY = theDataY[, -3]
theDataY = rbind(theDataY, tunedDf)
theDataY$type = as.factor(c(rep("Original", 20),
                  rep("SVM Prediction", 20),
                  rep("Tuned SVM", 20)))
ggplot(theDataY[20:60,], aes(x = x, y = y, colour = type)) + 
     geom_point(size = 2) +
     geom_line() +
     geom_point(data = theDataY[1:20,], colour = "black") +
     xlim(0, 20) +
     ylim(-5, 45) +
     theme_economist() + # From ggthemes
     ggtitle("SVM Prediction")
